1 of 3 ways.

The first option is to walk. This is what most people do, so it is very safe and common and has all the normal risks you would think walking in a large city would be. The second option is a motorcycle or motor scooter. This is also relatively safe and common because most people drive them at very low speeds or walk with a motor scooter attached to the back of a bicycle. The final option is to take a taxi. This option is the most expensive and is generally reserved for the people who live closest, and therefore do not need to walk.

For this reason, if more and more people are able to afford motor vehicles while smaller percentages of people are still able to take taxis or motor cycles then the majority of people will walk to purchase their food. The cost to walk or take a motor cycle to the store is covered by a modest income, but a car becomes a very costly commitment for those same people.

The evidence of how this capitalist trend has impacted Algeria is all around you. Western style clothing, smartphones, and cars become more prevalent across the inclination every week. Formal dining at restaurants, extremely high gas, water, and consumer goods prices become more prevalent as well. Consumers are not earning more of these goods, but the demand of their existence is growing.

This is just one example, but it’s a great way to recognize how the world around us is changing, and more specifically, how your purpose as a professional is changing.
